content: When I downloaded the offline mode it automatically deletes it,by storage booster(samsung in built app) so i cann't use it even i purchased the full version..I have already told them by email ,they are not listening to me...
replyContent:
Hi,

A known issue with users that have some kind of cleaner/optimizer app on the device and it's set to remove "large/big" files automatically. 

The dictionary database is one large file that provides offline access so these "optimization" apps directly targets it every day. The simple remedy is to change the setting of the cleaner app.

content: I was looking for a dictionary app that was ads free, could be used as the main dictionary in my reading app moon reader, and it had to be reasonably quick when looking up words. This app fulfill my above requirements and more. For example, I didn't like learning one new word per day notification at first. However, after I've learned several new words, I begin to see the benefit of learning new words with such method. But only it expands my vocabulary, also remembering one new word per day is much easier then memorizing say twenty new words per day.
The dictionary itself is great, but constant nagging for a review is not (it is a paid app).

I like the etymologies given. It helps remember the original meaning of the word. Also, unlike the American dictionaries, which just give current usage, right or wrong, the OED tells one what the usage is SUPPOSED to be. (I ignore the OED spellings, of course.)

content: Brilliant I rate it 10/10
Easy to use and very comprehensive.
OXFORD DICTIONARY

Oxford remains a standard bearer for the English language. With this tome-dispensing app you get up to date items. But while google might offer the content free there are still places even in London and Oxford where you cannot get internet or need to sign up to someone's wifi. This works like a tome, not an internet site.

MS need to sort out their purchase procedures. I have just installed the presented (free) version, was then prompted to get the paid version,  which I did. I then found I had both, using up space. I went to uninstall the free version,  and found I'd lost both, and in the process cancelled my purchase. Daft.
Very nice dictionary with latest and large collection of words. Easy to use. Examples and audio pronunciation are great.

This dictionary is functional, but the UI appears awfully dated. Also, compared with the Merriam-Webster's dictionary app (developer: Merriam-Webster Inc.), it's clear that M-W's app is superior: the UI is better, the sound quality of pronounciation is superor (*way* superior), and the words have more usage examples. Another disappointment is that you can't highlight a word in your favorite ebook reader and 'share' to this dictionary app. Well, this is still Oxford Dictionary, if you're looking for one. But I'd expected a better implementation than this.
What a shame that this premium dictionary doesn't work inside your own another premium application Mobisystem Office Suite? While google search and free dictionary works there.
replyContent:
Hi Nasar,
Thank you for writing to us. The Oxford Dictionary of English is integrated in the OfficeSuite but the integrations is available through the OfficeSuite. To access the dictionary open OfficeSuite and tap on the "Aa" icon on the Side bar. -MobiSystems Support Team-
